sertEqual(resolved_metadata_path, metadata_path.resolve())\\n   191\\t\\n   192\\t            serialized = json.dumps(metadata_a, indent=2, sort_keys=True)\\n   193\\t            self.assertEqual(metadata_path.read_text(encoding=\\\"utf-8\\\"), serialized)\\n   194\\t\\n   195\\t\\n   196\\tif __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\":\\n   197\\t    unittest.main()\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260322T023042Z/FW-M8B-001_Freeze_a_versioned_retinal_input_bundle_contract_and_ommatidial_sampling_design_note/stdout.jsonl:112:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_61\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"nl -ba docs/retinal_bundle_design.md | sed -n '1,260p'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"     1\\t# Milestone 8B Retinal Input Bundle Contract And Ommatidial Sampling Choice\\n     2\\t\\n     3\\tThis note freezes the Milestone 8B handoff between world-facing visual sources\\n     4\\tand fly-facing retinal input so later scene, simulator, and UI work can target\\n     5\\tone explicit bundle contract, one explicit meaning of a retinal frame, and one\\n     6\\texplicit set of coordinate and timing conventions.\\n     7\\t\\n     8\\t## Contract summary\\n     9\\t\\n    10\\tThe canonical Milestone 8B retinal contract is `retinal_input_bundle.v1`.\\n    11\\t\\n    12\\tThe bundle owns:\\n    13\\t\\n    14\\t- one canonical bundle ID built from upstream source identity plus the retinal\\n    15\\t  sampling-spec hash\\n    16\\t- one authoritative metadata file that records the retinal-contract version,\\n    17\\t  design-note version, source identity, eye ordering, ommatidial ordering,\\n    18\\t  frame timing, coordinate conventions, sampling-kernel settings, and signal\\n    19\\t  conventions\\n    20\\t- one optional sampled frame archive for deterministic local replay\\n    21\\t\\n    22\\tThe canonical layout is:\\n    23\\t\\n    24\\t- `config.paths.processed_retinal_dir/bundles/<source_kind>/<source_family>/<source_name>/<source_hash>/<retinal_spec_hash>/retinal_input_bundle.json`\\n    25\\t- `config.paths.processed_retinal_dir/bundles/<source_kind>/<source_family>/<source_name>/<source_hash>/<retinal_spec_hash>/retinal_frames.npz`\\n    26\\t\\n    27\\t`retinal_input_bundle.v1` intentionally keeps the surface small. More sidecars\\n    28\\tmay be added later, but those paths are the stable discovery surface for the\\n    29\\tretinal recording itself.\\n    30\\t\\n    31\\t## Candidate abstraction families\\n    32\\t\\n    33\\t### Direct per-ommatidium irradiance\\n    34\\t\\n    35\\tDefinition:\\n    36\\t\\n    37\\t- each sampled frame stores one irradiance value per eye and per ommatidium\\n    38\\t- later consumers can derive temporal filters, feature maps, or UI rasters from\\n    39\\t  this detector-level representation\\n    40\\t\\n    41\\tAdvantages:\\n    42\\t\\n    43\\t- closest to the fly-facing sampling event the later simulator actually needs\\n    44\\t- keeps bundle identity tied to stable detector ordering rather than a display\\n    45\\t  raster convention\\n    46\\t- easiest representation to compare across simulator, QA, and UI consumers\\n    47\\t- avoids silently baking later feature-extraction assumptions into the contract\\n    48\\t\\n    49\\tCosts:\\n    50\\t\\n    51\\t- less convenient for human preview than an image-like raster\\n    52\\t- later UIs need a detector-layout-aware rendering step\\n    53\\t\\n    54\\t### Eye-image raster intermediates\\n    55\\t\\n    56\\tDefinition:\\n    57\\t\\n    58\\t- first resample each eye into an image grid, then treat that raster as the\\n    59\\t  retinal handoff\\n    60\\t\\n    61\\tAdvantages:\\n    62\\t\\n    63\\t- easy to display and debug visually\\n    64\\t- fits commodity image tooling well\\n    65\\t\\n    66\\tCosts:\\n    67\\t\\n    68\\t- introduces one extra resampling layer before the simulator ever sees the\\n    69\\t  input\\n    70\\t- binds bundle identity to a raster layout that the fly does not physically\\n    71\\t  observe\\n    72\\t- makes detector indexing and acceptance kernels harder to audit\\n    73\\t\\n    74\\t### Higher-level retinotopic feature maps\\n    75\\t\\n    76\\tDefinition:\\n    77\\t\\n    78\\t- treat motion-energy channels, contrast filters, or other early visual feature\\n    79\\t  maps as the primary retinal output\\n    80\\t\\n    81\\tAdvantages:\\n    82\\t\\n    83\\t- can align directly with some later model families\\n    84\\t- compact for task-specific baselines\\n    85\\t\\n    86\\tCosts:\\n    87\\t\\n    88\\t- bakes model assumptions into the contract too early\\n    89\\t- blocks fair comparisons between different simulator or front-end pipelines\\n    90\\t- loses the detector-level input that later QA and ablation work needs\\n    91\\t\\n    92\\t## Decision\\n    93\\t\\n    94\\tThe default Milestone 8B abstraction is `direct_per_ommatidium_irradiance`.\\n    95\\t\\n    96\\t`retinal_input_bundle.v1` serializes only that family. Eye-image rasters and\\n    97\\thigher-level feature maps remain valid derived views or future-contract options,\\n    98\\tbut they are not the authoritative handoff in this version.\\n    99\\t\\n   100\\tWhy this is the default:\\n   101\\t\\n   102\\t- Milestones 8C, 9, and 10 need one unambiguous detector-level definition of\\n   103\\t  “the same retinal input”\\n   104\\t- later simulators should share one source of truth before they add their own\\n   105\\t  filtering or state abstractions\\n   106\\t- UI code can always render detector values into a view, but it cannot recover\\n   107\\t  omitted detector semantics from an arbitrary raster or feature stack\\n   108\\t\\n   109\\t## What one retinal frame means\\n   110\\t\\n   111\\tOne canonical retinal frame is a dense `time x eye x ommatidium` sample table\\n   112\\twith:\\n   113\\t\\n   114\\t- eye axis order fixed by the recorded `eye_order`, default `[left, right]`\\n   115\\t- eye indexing fixed by `axis_index_matches_eye_order`\\n   116\\t- ommatidial ordering fixed by `stable_eye_local_ommatidium_index`\\n   117\\t- one shared `ommatidium_count_per_eye` recorded in the bundle metadata\\n   118\\t- value semantics fixed to `per_ommatidium_linear_irradiance`\\n   119\\t\\n   120\\tMeaning:\\n   121\\t\\n   122\\t- frame `t` is the binocular detector snapshot for one sample-hold time bin\\n   123\\t- later simulator and UI code may reshape or render the data, but they may not\\n   124\\t  silently reorder the eye axis or ommatidial axis while still claiming they\\n   125\\t  are consuming the same bundle\\n   126\\t\\n   127\\t## Coordinate conventions\\n   128\\t\\n   129\\tAll Cartesian frames are right-handed.\\n   130\\t\\n   131\\t### World frame\\n   132\\t\\n   133\\t- frame name: `world_cartesian`\\n   134\\t- origin: `scene_defined_world_origin`\\n   135\\t- axes: `+x forward`, `+y left`, `+z up`\\n   136\\t\\n   137\\t### Body frame\\n   138\\t\\n   139\\t- frame name: `fly_body`\\n   140\\t- origin: `thorax_center`\\n   141\\t- axes: `+x anterior`, `+y left`, `+z dorsal`\\n   142\\t\\n   143\\t### Head frame\\n   144\\t\\n   145\\t- frame name: `fly_head`\\n   146\\t- origin: `head_center`\\n   147\\t- axes: `+x anterior`, `+y left`, `+z dorsal`\\n   148\\t- zero-pose alignment: aligned with the body frame\\n   149\\t\\n   150\\t### Eye frame\\n   151\\t\\n   152\\t- frame name: `compound_eye_local`\\n   153\\t- origin: `eye_center`\\n   154\\t- axes: `+z optical_axis_outward`, `+x dorsal`, `+y completes_right_handed_frame`\\n   155\\t- positive azimuth is toward `+y`\\n   156\\t- positive elevation is toward `+x`\\n   157\\t\\n   158\\tMeaning:\\n   159\\t\\n   160\\t- later geometry code may choose any internal transform implementation it wants\\n   161\\t  as long as it lands on these same external frame semantics\\n   162\\t- left and right eyes may have different rigid transforms from the head frame,\\n   163\\t  but they must share the same local eye-axis naming and angular sign\\n   164\\t  conventions\\n   165\\t\\n   166\\t## Timing and signal conventions\\n   167\\t\\n   168\\t### Temporal sampling\\n   169\\t\\n   170\\tMilestone 8B uses the same conservative timing convention as Milestone 8A:\\n   171\\t\\n   172\\t- time unit: milliseconds\\n   173\\t- frame timing block records `time_origin_ms`, `dt_ms`, `duration_ms`, and\\n   174\\t  `frame_count`\\n   175\\t- sampling mode: `sample_hold`\\n   176\\t\\n   177\\tMeaning:\\n   178\\t\\n   179\\t- retinal frame `k` is authoritative for the half-open interval\\n   180\\t  `[time_origin_ms + k * dt_ms, time_origin_ms + (k + 1) * dt_ms)`\\n   181\\t- later simulators may integrate internally at finer timesteps, but they must\\n   182\\t  preserve the same piecewise-constant bundle values at the retinal frame\\n   183\\t  boundaries unless a later contract revision says otherwise\\n   184\\t\\n   185\\t### Signal convention\\n   186\\t\\n   187\\tMilestone 8B fixes one conservative detector-value convention:\\n   188\\t\\n   189\\t- encoding: `linear_irradiance_unit_interval`\\n   190\\t- minimum value: `0.0`\\n   191\\t- neutral value: `0.5`\\n   192\\t- maximum value: `1.0`\\n   193\\t- contrast semantics: `signed_delta_from_neutral_gray`\\n   194\\t- positive polarity means `brighter_than_neutral`\\n   195\\t\\n   196\\tMeaning:\\n   197\\t\\n   198\\t- the detector values preserve the Milestone 8A linear luminance convention\\n   199\\t  rather than introducing display gamma or simulator-specific normalization\\n   200\\t- out-of-range sampling results must be clipped into `[0.0, 1.0]`, and that\\n   201\\t  clipping is part of the contract\\n   202\\t\\n   203\\t## Sampling-kernel semantics\\n   204\\t\\n   205\\tThe default Milestone 8B sampling kernel is\\n   206\\t`gaussian_acceptance_weighted_mean`.\\n   207\\t\\n   208\\tEvery bundle records:\\n   209\\t\\n   210\\t- kernel family\\n   211\\t- acceptance angle in degrees\\n   212\\t- support radius in degrees\\n   213\\t- kernel normalization rule\\n   214\\t- out-of-field policy and background fill value\\n   215\\t\\n   216\\tMeaning:\\n   217\\t\\n   218\\t- later samplers may optimize the implementation, but the realized detector\\n   219\\t  values must remain equivalent to the recorded kernel settings\\n   220\\t- out-of-field handling is never implicit; the background fill behavior is part\\n   221\\t  of the reproducibility contract\\n   222\\t\\n   223\\t## Invariants later milestones must preserve\\n   224\\t\\n   225\\tLater scene, simulator, and UI milestones must preserve these invariants when\\n   226\\tthey claim to reuse `retinal_input_bundle.v1`:\\n   227\\t\\n   228\\t- bundle identity is the tuple `(contract_version, source_kind, source_family,\\n   229\\t  source_name, source_hash, retinal_spec_hash)`\\n   230\\t- the authoritative source identity recorded in `source_reference` must not be\\n   231\\t  replaced with an ad hoc file path or unnamed frame stack\\n   232\\t- `direct_per_ommatidium_irradiance` remains the source-of-truth handoff even\\n   233\\t  if a downstream consumer also builds rasters or feature maps\\n   234\\t- eye ordering and ommatidial ordering are explicit contract fields, not\\n   235\\t  consumer-defined guesses\\n   236\\t- world, body, head, and eye frame semantics may not be mirrored or rotated\\n   237\\t  silently between stages\\n   238\\t- time stays in milliseconds with sample-hold semantics unless a later contract\\n   239\\t  revision explicitly supersedes this one\\n   240\\t- detector values stay in the recorded linear-irradiance convention; later\\n   241\\t  contrast or adaptation transforms must be explicit derived steps\\n   242\\t\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
